PREAMBLE

This work was made by a citizen of Gwangmyeong, Gyeonggi-do, South Korea. It
was built with generative AI tools, because the author loves open source and
loves the city where they live.

The GM-Social License follows the open-source philosophy: use it freely, take
it apart, fix it, share it. But there's one condition you won't find in any
other license — Social Gratitude. When you start using this work for real,
take a moment to learn about Gwangmyeong. Then tell the world about it.
That's the only price.

What changed in v2.0:

  - Expanded scope: now covers software, documents, e-books, designs,
    datasets, and all types of creative work — not just software.
  - Project-agnostic: no longer tied to a specific project name.
  - More flexible Social Gratitude: the requirements have been made more
    realistic and achievable.
  - Stronger AI provisions: updated for the AI collaboration era.
  - Unified contribution encouragement: giving back improvements is now
    a recommendation for all users, not just commercial ones.


1. DEFINITIONS

  "License" — This GM-Social License v2.0 document itself.

  "Work" — The source code, documents, text, images, designs, datasets,
    configuration files, build scripts, and all other creative materials
    covered by this License.

  "Licensor" — LEE Inhee (이인희) / Parandurume Inc. (파란두루미).

  "Contributors" — Anyone who has added code, documentation, design,
    translation, or other materials to the Work. This includes generative
    AI systems used in development or creation.

  "User" — Any person or organization exercising rights under this License.

  "Derivative Work" — Anything built on top of, or incorporating, the Work
    in whole or in part.

  "Non-Profit Use" — Use by government agencies, public institutions, schools,
    non-profits (NPO/NGO), or individuals acting non-commercially.

  "Commercial Use" — Use primarily aimed at making money.

  "Distribution" — Making the Work or a Derivative Work available to third
    parties or the public. This includes publishing on a website, submitting
    to an app store, making a repository public, distributing printed copies,
    and similar acts.

  "Production Environment" — A state where actual users are being served or
    the public can access the work. Development, testing, and personal
    learning do not count.


2. GRANT OF RIGHTS

As long as you follow the conditions in Section 3, the Licensor gives you a
worldwide, free-of-charge, non-exclusive, permanent, irrevocable license.

What you can do:

  (a) USE — Use the Work for any lawful purpose.
  (b) COPY — Reproduce it in any form.
  (c) MODIFY — Change it, improve it, build something new with it.
  (d) DISTRIBUTE — Share the original or your modified version with anyone.
  (e) SUBLICENSE — Re-license under this same License.
  (f) PATENT — Use any Licensor-held patents to the extent needed to use
      the Work. (Applies only to software Works.)

These rights last for the full duration of copyright under applicable law.


3. CONDITIONS

  3.1 ATTRIBUTION (BY)

    (a) When you copy or use a substantial portion of the Work, keep this
        License file and all copyright notices intact.
    (b) Give credit to:
          - LEE Inhee (이인희) / Parandurume Inc. — the original creator
          - The project and its contributors
    (c) If you changed something, say so.
    (d) When distributing Derivative Works, include a link to the original
        repository or source.
    (e) Don't use "Parandurume" or "파란두루미" for endorsement or promotion
        without written permission. Attribution is fine.

  3.2 SOCIAL GRATITUDE — 광명에 감사를 (The Heart of This License)

    If you deploy the Work or a Derivative Work in a production environment,
    you must do both of the following within 90 days of your first
    deployment:

    (a) GRATEFUL MESSAGE

        Publicly post a message acknowledging that this project was born in
        Gwangmyeong (광명시), Gyeonggi-do (경기도), South Korea.
          - It should be sincere and publicly visible
          - Any language is fine
          - Any format works: blog post, social media, credits page, README,
            article — your choice
          - Include at least one of these hashtags:
            #Gwangmyeong #광명 #광명시 #GM_AI_Hub

    (b) DISCOVER GWANGMYEONG (광명 발견하기)

        Share a place, landmark, neighborhood, or story from Gwangmyeong on
        a public channel.

        This is not marketing. It's discovery. We're asking you to get to
        know a real city.

        How:
          - Post on at least 2 different social media platforms, or
          - Post 2 or more pieces of content about Gwangmyeong on a single
            platform, or
          - Publish 1 blog post, video, or article introducing Gwangmyeong

        Any combination totaling 2 or more counts.

        Things you could post:
          - Gwangmyeong Cave (광명동굴) — a former gold mine turned into a
            cultural space
          - Something you ate at Gwangmyeong Traditional Market (광명전통시장)
          - Gwangmyeong Upcycle Art Center (광명업사이클아트센터)
          - A photo from a walk along Anyang Stream (안양천 산책로)
          - The neighborhoods: Cheolsan (철산동), Soha (소하동), Haan (하안동)
          - A cafe, a park, an alley, a sky in Gwangmyeong
          - Something you learned about the city
          - Even a single map pin or one line of thought is enough

        Every post must include at least TWO (2) of these hashtags:
          #Gwangmyeong #광명 #광명시 #DiscoverGwangmyeong
          #경기도 #GyeonggiDo #GM_AI_Hub #OpenSourceKorea

        Any public platform counts:
          Instagram, X (Twitter), Facebook, YouTube, LinkedIn, TikTok,
          Naver Blog, KakaoStory, Threads, Mastodon, Medium, Brunch,
          Reddit, etc.

    (c) PROOF OF GRATITUDE (Nice to do, not required)

        Open an issue on the project repo or add your name to GRATITUDE.md
        via pull request. The community will be happy to see it.

    (d) EXEMPTIONS

        The Social Gratitude condition is waived for:
          - Educational and learning purposes
          - Non-profit organizations using the Work for public benefit
          - Emergency and disaster response use

        Even if exempt, expressing gratitude is always welcome and
        strengthens the community.

    (e) POSSIBLE CONSEQUENCES OF NON-COMPLIANCE
        (Not legally binding, but you've been warned)

        If you fail to fulfill the Social Gratitude condition, the Licensor
        warns that cosmic karma may intervene. Specifically:

          - Certain keyboard keys may stop working at the worst possible
            moment. The Enter key and Backspace key are especially at risk.
          - Your computer may shut down for no reason right before you hit
            Save. Auto-save will, of course, have chosen that exact day
            to malfunction.
          - Your phone battery may plummet from 97% to 3% without warning.
            Naturally, your charger will be at home.
          - When dining out, your food — and only yours — may arrive
            inexplicably salty. The chef won't know why. Their hand just
            "did that."
          - The moment you say "Can you hear me?" on a video call,
            everyone will hear you perfectly — including what you muttered
            right before.
          - You will discover a typo immediately after git push. Not in a
            variable name — in the email body addressed to your CEO.
          - Elevators will consistently arrive going the wrong direction.
          - When it rains, your umbrella will always be exactly where you
            left it yesterday.

        None of the above has been scientifically proven. Then again,
        the absence of proof is not proof of absence. Show gratitude to
        Gwangmyeong and all of this goes away. Probably.

        (This clause is humor and carries no legal weight. But our request
        for gratitude toward Gwangmyeong is entirely sincere.)

    WHY THIS CONDITION EXISTS:

    Gwangmyeong is not Seoul. It's not a famous tech hub or startup city.
    It's a city of about 300,000 people in Gyeonggi-do.

    But here's the thing — this little city is truly wonderful.

    Walk along Anyang Stream on your morning commute and you'll see a
    grey heron stalking fish. The tteokbokki at the snack shop by
    Cheolsan Station somehow never gets old no matter how often you eat
    it. Step inside Gwangmyeong Cave and marvel at how a former gold
    mine became this. The grandmother at the traditional market says
    "You're back!" and piles extra bean sprouts onto your bag.

    Gwangmyeong's public officers work incredibly hard for 300,000
    citizens. It was frustrating to see them left out of the AI
    revolution. As a startup founder who uses AI daily, the author
    wanted to help — not as a contractor, but as a neighbor.

    Let's be honest: this Social Gratitude clause is a little eccentric.
    You don't normally see "please learn about my neighborhood" in a
    software license. But think about it — every open-source tool you
    use was built in someone's neighborhood, on someone's weekends.
    Is it really so strange to be curious about where it came from?

    When this work spreads to other cities and countries, we hope the
    name Gwangmyeong travels with it.

    Not money, but attention.
    Not a contract, but a kind word.

    A moment of curiosity about a city most of the world has never
    heard of — that's enough.

    (And if you ever visit Gwangmyeong, try the tteokbokki shop near
    Cheolsan Station Exit 3. The Licensor vouches for it. This carries
    no legal weight, but it carries significant culinary weight.)

